==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lithography
<hw>Li*thog"ra*phy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>lithographie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The art or process of
putting designs or writing, with a greasy material, on stone, and of
producing printed impressions therefrom. The process depends, in the
main, upon the antipathy between grease and water, which prevents a
printing ink containing oil from adhering to wetted parts of the stone
not covered by the design. See <cref>Lithographic limestone</cref>,
under <er>Lithographic</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a printing process for reproducing images, using any
flat surface, such as a metal plate, in a manner similar to
<er>lithography{1}</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The process of producing patterns on semiconductor
crystals by exposing photosensitive coatings on a matrix, such as
silicon, to light patterns in the form desired for the circuit, and
subsequently treating (e.g., chemically) the patterns thus formed in
such a way as to create integrated semiconductor circuits with the
desired properties. This is the principle method (1990's) to create the
high-density integrated circuits used in the digital computers on which
you are reading this.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lithoidal</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Lithoid</ent>⟦br⟧
